&lt;li id="fn-2"&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is for the "why don't you just..." crowd. This is about a proprietary application owned by my employer, so I can't go into detail. But trust me that I can't delete the Auth0 accounts, and there's no in-application flag I can set to block a user at the moment.&lt;a class="footnote" href="#fnref-2"&gt;‚Ü©&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li id="fn-3"&gt;&lt;p&gt;TIL there's more to blocking users in Auth0 than blocking them by hand like I'm doing. Apparently there are Auth0 features for automatically blocking new users who exhibit bot-like behavior. This was news to me as my employer's application is a fairly niche web app for medical clinics. We're not seeing nearly enough traffic to be subject to scripted sign-ups.&lt;a class="footnote" href="#fnref-3"&gt;‚Ü©&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
